subsection.p:
The other units of length in the English/Imperial system have the following relations to inch; you can convert them in multiples of meters (i.e., into SI units) by first converting them into inches, and then using this exact conversion of inches into centimeters.

	\amp 1\ \text{ft} =  12\ \text{in} 
	\amp 1\ \text{yd}= 3\ \text{ft} 
	\amp 1\ \text{mi}= 1760\ \text{yd} 

The English unit of mass is a pound (\text{lb}) or pound-mass, which is approximately 


	1\ \text{lb} = 453.59237\ \text{grams} \approx 453.6\ \text{grams}.

The unit of pound (lb) for mass is sometimes confused with a similar name for force, called pound force (lbf) which stands for the weight of a pound of something. The relation to the unit of force in SI unit, called Newton (N) turns out to be

	1\, \text{lbf} \approx 4.448\, \text{N}.

This is obtained from the formula F=mg with m=1\,\text{lb}\approx 0.4536\,\text{kg} and g=9.81\,\text{m}/\text{s}^2. The unit of Newton stands for 

	 \text{N} \equiv \text{kg}\, \frac{\text{m}}{\text{s}^2}.

solution.p:
You can start with 20 minutes and then multiply with a fraction of second [the unit desired] to minute [the unit to be converted] whose value is 1.  The fraction is obtained by the conversion of 60 seconds in 1 minute.

	 20\, \text{min}\ \amp =  20\, \text{min} \times \frac{60\, \text{sec}}{1\, \text{min}}
	 \amp =  20\, \cancel{\text{min}} \times \frac{60\ \text{sec}}{1\,  \cancel{\text{min}}}
	 \amp = 1200\, \text{sec}.,

sidebyside.p:
				The calculation is presented below.  You should note that when I used the calculator I got way too many digits than the three digits in 2.54 that went into the calculation, so I put in another step where the final answer was rounded off to three digits.  This happens a lot in calculations and you should learn to round off numbers to correct number of digits. I will show you later a consistent way of rounding off that is commonly practised. 

					10\ \text{in}^2\ \amp = 10\ \text{in} \times \text{in}
					 \amp =  10\ \cancel{\text{in}} \times \cancel{\text{in}}\times \frac{2.54\ \text{cm}}{1\ \cancel{\text{in}}}\times \frac{2.54\ \text{cm}}{1\ \cancel{\text{in}}}
					\amp \ \ \text{(two factors needed)}
                  	 \amp = 10\times2.54\text{ cm}\ \times2.54\text{ cm}
                  	 \amp =  64.516\ \text{[from calculator]}\ \text{cm}^2
                  	 \amp = 64.5\ \text{cm}^2.
